{"key":"post-12795400","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12795400</id>\n<content>The purpose of the plenum is to allow a uniform pressure to be exerted over the entire surface of the back of the filter.&amp;nbsp; If that is achieved, the plenum is large enough.&amp;nbsp; If you're putting the blower inside the plenum, other issues with turbulence arise, and testing is going to be required.&amp;nbsp; A suitable anemometer can be had for around $200 and is a good investment if you're engineering your own unit.&amp;nbsp; A good rule of thumb for an external mounted blower is to make the plenum at least as thick as the filter in order to have a space to pressurize, but that's not a hard and fast rule.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The bottom line is if the anemometer(or a candle flame for a cheaper alternative) indicates the same amount of airflow over the entire working area, you've achieved laminar flow.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12795862</next>\n<prev>12795388</prev>\n<first>12786134</first>\n<last>12867397</last>\n<when>1277390665</when>\n<utime>06/24/10 05:44 PM</utime>\n</post>"}